2861 To PAOLo SADOLETO.

De Praeparatione p. 154. Freiburg.

N. p. 1087: Lond. xxvii. 21: LB. 1254. 30 August 1533.

[Paul Sadoleto, 15οὸψ1569, was the son of a cousin of the cardinal. Like the cardinal, he was born at Modena. and educated at Ferrara, where he was taught by Lilius Gyraldus. On the death of his father he seems to have gone with the cardinal to Carpentras. He shared the cardinal's human- istic interestS, and devoted himself to the study of Aristotle, Cicero, and the Greek and Latin Fathers; besides writing poetry both in Latin and in the vernacular. In 1533 Clement vn appointed him coadjutor to the cardinal in the see of Carpentras, with the reversion of the bishopric on his kinsman's death. On the accession of Paul 111 (1535), he went to Italy to pay his respects to the new Pope, and spent some time in Rome and Padua. In 1538 he accompanied the cardinal to Nice, in connexion with the truce there made between the Emperor, the Pope, and Francis 1. In 1552 Pope Julius 111 called him to Rome, and made him his principal diplomatic secretary. On the death of Julius he returned to Carpentras; where he died in 1569. Togcthcr with Antonius Florebellus he was responsible for the edition of the letters of Jacopo Sadoleto, published at Lyons by Gryphius in 1550; the last section of the book consists of letters of the cardinal to Paul Sadoleto (six of the letters belong to the year 1535: two to 1543; one to 1546).
